# Fix Docker Socket Mount for macOS and Windows Hosts

## Root Cause

In `startDocker()` (`internal/runner/docker.go`, lines 334–340), `sockFlags` (the `-v socket:/var/run/docker.sock` bind-mount) is only built when `h.OS == "linux"`. macOS and Windows docker-mode runners start without any socket mount, so the container has no Docker daemon reachable at `/var/run/docker.sock`.

```334:340:internal/runner/docker.go
	var sockFlags string
	if h.OS == "linux" {
		if err := dockerEngineSockPreflightCheck(h, hcfg.DockerSocket); err != nil {
			return err
		}
		sockFlags = dockerEngineSockFlags(h, hcfg.DockerSocket)
	}
```

## Platform Behavior

- **Linux:** `/var/run/docker.sock` (or custom path). Needs `--group-add <GID>`. Already works.
- **macOS (darwin):** Docker Desktop / OrbStack / Colima expose the socket at `/var/run/docker.sock` (via symlink). The Docker CLI on macOS maps bind-mounts correctly. No `--group-add` needed (all processes in the VM have access). The `docker_socket` config field should be allowed on macOS for Colima users with non-default paths (e.g. `~/.colima/default/docker.sock`).
- **Windows:** Docker Desktop (Linux containers mode) exposes `/var/run/docker.sock` inside the Hyper-V/WSL2 VM. Running `docker run -v /var/run/docker.sock:/var/run/docker.sock` on Windows in Linux-containers mode correctly maps the VM-internal socket. No `--group-add` needed. No `docker_socket` override supported (named pipe, not a configurable path).

## Changes

### 1. `internal/runner/docker.go` — extend `startDocker` to mount socket on darwin

Change the `if h.OS == "linux"` block to also handle `darwin`, but skip `--group-add`:

```go
switch h.OS {
case "linux":
    if err := dockerEngineSockPreflightCheck(h, hcfg.DockerSocket); err != nil {
        return err
    }
    sockFlags = dockerEngineSockFlags(h, hcfg.DockerSocket)
case "darwin":
    sockPath := hcfg.DockerSocket
    if sockPath == "" {
        sockPath = defaultDockerSocket
    }
    if err := dockerEngineSockPreflightCheck(h, sockPath); err != nil {
        return err
    }
    // On macOS the VM socket is accessible to all processes; no --group-add needed.
    sockFlags = fmt.Sprintf("-v %s:/var/run/docker.sock ", sockPath)
case "windows":
    // Docker Desktop (Linux containers mode) maps /var/run/docker.sock automatically
    // via the Hyper-V/WSL2 VM; bind-mount it the same way as Linux/macOS.
    sockFlags = fmt.Sprintf("-v /var/run/docker.sock:/var/run/docker.sock ")
}
```

Also add a new `darwinDockerSockFlags` helper to keep `dockerEngineSockFlags` Linux-specific (GID stat logic).

### 2. `internal/config/config.go` — allow `docker_socket` on darwin

Change the validation:

```go
if h.DockerSocket != "" {
    if h.OS != "linux" && h.OS != "darwin" {
        return fmt.Errorf("host %q: docker_socket is only supported on Linux and macOS hosts", name)
    }
    ...
}
```

Update the comment on `DockerSocket` field:

```go
DockerSocket string `yaml:"docker_socket"` // override Docker socket path (Linux/macOS; default /var/run/docker.sock)
```

### 3. `internal/doctor/doctor.go` — add socket check for darwin

Extend `checkDocker` to call socket verification for `darwin` hosts (using the same `checkLinuxDockerSocket` logic, renamed or a new `checkUnixDockerSocket`):

```go
if h.OS == "linux" || h.OS == "darwin" {
    checkUnixDockerSocket(w, hostName, h, hcfg, runners, r)
}
```

Rename `checkLinuxDockerSocket` → `checkUnixDockerSocket` and adjust help text (no GID message on darwin).

### 4. `internal/runner/docker_test.go` — add tests

- `Test_startDocker_darwin_mountsSocket`: verify `sockFlags` is set for darwin
- `Test_darwinDockerSockFlags_noGroupAdd`: verify no `--group-add` in darwin path
- `Test_startDocker_windows_mountsSocket`: verify socket mount is present for windows

### 5. Documentation updates

- `docs/content/guides/linux-on-macos.md`: Remove "docker_socket is not supported on macOS" statement; add that `docker_socket` can be set for Colima non-default paths
- `docs/content/guides/linux-on-windows.md`: No change needed (docs already correctly state socket is mounted; just the code was missing it)
- `docs/content/host-setup.md`: Update macOS section to mention socket mount behavior; update `docker_socket` section to mention macOS support

